<title>

Heron's Formula for Triangular Area

</title>
</head>


<body bgcolor=3D"#ffffff">

<p>
</p><h3>
Contents
</h3>
<p>
<a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m309-01a/goon/main.ht=
ml">Main Page</a>
</p><center>
</center>
<a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m309-01a/goon/refer.h=
tml">References and Links</a>
<p>
</p><hr>
<p>


</p><center>
<h1>Heron's Formula for Triangular Area</h1>
</center>



<p>
</p><center>
<h2>
THEOREM
</h2>
</center>

<p>
</p><center>
<img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m309-01a/goon/fig6.g=
if">
</center>
<center>
<b>
Figure 6
</b>
</center>

<p>
For a triangle having sides of length <i>a</i>, <i>b</i>, and <i>c</i> and =
area <i>K</i>, we have=20
</p><center>
<i>K</i> =3D sqrt[ <i>s</i>(<i>s - a</i>)(<i>s - b</i>)(<i>s - c</i>) ],
</center>
where <i>s</i> =3D =BD(<i>a</i> + <i>b</i> + <i>c</i>) is the triangle's se=
mi-perimeter.

<p>
</p><hr>

<p>
</p><center>
<h2>
PROOF
</h2>
</center>
Let <i>ABC</i> be an arbitrary triangle. Also, let the side <i>AB</i> be at=
 least as long as the other two sides (Figure 6).


<p>
Because the proof of Heron's Formula is "circuitous" and long, we'll divide=
 the proof into three main parts.




</p><p>
</p><h3>
Part A
</h3>
Let <i>O</i> be the center of the inscribed circle. Let <i>r</i> be the rad=
ius of this circle (Figure 7). As we can see, <i>OD</i> =3D <i>OE</i> =3D <=
i>OF</i> =3D <i>r</i>.
<p>
Now, applying the usual formula for the area of triangles, we get:
</p><p>
</p><center>
Area(<i>AOB</i>) =3D =BD(base)(height) =3D =BD(<i>AB</i>)(<i>OD</i>) =3D =
=BD<i>cr</i>
<p>
Area(<i>BOC</i>) =3D =BD(base)(height) =3D =BD(<i>BC</i>)(<i>OE</i>) =3D =
=BD<i>ar</i>
</p><p>
Area(<i>COA</i>) =3D =BD(base)(height) =3D =BD(<i>AC</i>)(<i>OF</i>) =3D =
=BD<i>br</i>
</p></center>
So,
<center>
<i>K</i> =3D Area(<i>ABC</i>) =3D Area(<i>AOB</i>) + Area(<i>BOC</i>) + Are=
a(<i>COA</i>)
</center>
By substitution,=20
<center>
<i>K</i> =3D =BD<i>cr</i> + =BD<i>ar</i> + =BD<i>br</i> =3D =BD<i>r</i>(<i>=
a</i> + <i>b</i> + <i>c</i>) =3D <i>rs</i>
</center>

<p>
</p><center>
<img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m309-01a/goon/fig7.g=
if">
</center>
<center>
<b>
Figure 7
</b>
</center>


<p>
</p><h3>
Part B
</h3>
Now, using Proposition 1, we can see that <i>ABC</i> is now made of three p=
airs of congruent triangles, namely
<center>
<i>AOD</i> is congruent to <i>AOF</i>
</center>
<center>
<i>BOD</i> is congruent to <i>BOE</i>
</center>
and <center><i>COE</i> is congruent to <i>COF</i></center>
These congruences follow by AAS. Since corresponding parts of congruent tri=
angles are congruent, we have
<center>
<i>AD</i> =3D <i>AF</i>, <i>BD</i> =3D <i>BE</i>, and <i>CE</i> =3D <i>CF</=
i>
</center>
<center>
while &lt;<i>AOD</i> =3D &lt;<i>AOF</i>, &lt;<i>BOD</i> =3D &lt;<i>BOE</i>,=
 and &lt;<i>COE</i> =3D &lt;<i>COF</i>.
</center>
<p>
Now, extend the triangle's base <i>AB</i> to a point <i>G</i>, such that <i=
>AG</i> =3D <i>CE</i>. Now,
</p><p>
<i>BG</i> =3D <i>BD</i> + <i>AD</i> + <i>AG</i> =3D <i>BD</i> + <i>AD</i> +=
 <i>CE</i> by construction
</p><center>
</center>
=3D =BD(2<i>BD</i> + 2<i>AD</i> + 2<i>CE</i>)
<center>
</center>
=3D =BD[(<i>BD</i> + <i>BE</i>) + (<i>AD</i> + <i>AF</i>) + (<i>CE</i> + <i=
>CF</i>)] by congruence
<center>
</center>
=3D =BD[(<i>BD</i> + <i>AD</i>) + (<i>BE</i> + <i>CE</i>) + (<i>AF</i> + <i=
>CF</i>)]
<center>
</center>
=3D =BD[<i>AB</i> + <i>BC</i> + <i>AC</i>]
<center>
</center>
=3D =BD(<i>c</i> + <i>a</i> + <i>b</i>) =3D <i>s</i>

<p>
Now, since <i>BG</i> =3D <i>s</i>,
</p><p>
<i>s</i> - <i>c</i> =3D <i>BG</i> - <i>AB</i> =3D <i>AG</i>
</p><p>
<i>s</i> - <i>b</i> =3D <i>BG</i> - <i>AC</i>
</p><center>
</center>
=3D (<i>BD</i> + <i>AD</i> + <i>AG</i>) - (<i>CF</i> + <i>AF</i>)
<center>
</center>
=3D (<i>BD</i> + <i>AD</i> + <i>CE</i>) - (<i>CE</i> + <i>AD</i>) =3D <i>BD=
</i> since <i>AF =3D AD</i>, <i>CF</i> =3D <i>CE</i> and <i>AG</i> =3D <i>C=
E</i>.
<center>
</center>
Likewise,
<center>
</center>
<i>s</i> - <i>a</i> =3D <i>BG</i> - <i>BC</i>
<center>
</center>
=3D (<i>BD</i> + <i>AD</i> + <i>AG</i>) - (<i>BE</i> + <i>CE</i>)
<center>
</center>
=3D (<i>BD</i> + <i>AD</i> + <i>CE</i>) - (<i>BD</i> + <i>CE</i>) =3D <i>AD=
</i> since <i>BD</i> =3D <i>BE</i> and <i>AG</i> =3D <i>CE</i>.
<p>
These equalities just help us to visualize the segments <i>s</i> - <i>a</i>=
, <i>s</i> - <i>b</i>, and <i>s</i> - <i>c</i>.

</p><p>
</p><h3>
Part C
</h3>
Now, construct <i>OL</i> such that it's perpendicular to <i>OB</i>, interse=
cting <i>AB</i> at <i>K</i> (Figure 8).

<p>
</p><center>
<img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m309-01a/goon/fig8.g=
if">
</center>
<center>
<b>
Figure 8
</b>
</center>



<p>
Next, construct <i>AM</i> such that it's perpendicular to <i>AB</i>, inters=
ecting <i>OL</i> at <i>H</i> (Figure 9).

</p><p>
</p><center>
<img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m309-01a/goon/fig9.g=
if">
</center>
<center>
<b>
Figure 9
</b>
</center>

<p>
Next, connect <i>BH</i> (Figure 10).

</p><p>
</p><center>
<img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m309-01a/goon/fig10.=
gif">
</center>
<center>
<b>
Figure 10
</b>
</center>



<p>
By Proposition 4, the quadrilateral AHBO is a cyclic quadrilateral.
</p><center>
</center>
By Proposition 5, we know that &lt;<i>AHB</i> + &lt;<i>AOB</i> =3D 180 degr=
ees. <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(*)</font></b>

<p>
Please don't be discouraged with the following algebra. These can be visual=
ized using Figure 10.


</p><p>
Now, let's focus on the angles about <i>O</i>.
</p><center>
</center>
From the congruences in part B, we see that
<center>
&lt;<i>FOA</i> =3D &lt;<i>DOA</i>, &lt;<i>DOB</i> =3D &lt;<i>EOB</i>, and &=
lt;<i>EOC</i> =3D &lt;<i>FOC</i>. <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(**)</font></b=
>
</center>
Obviously,=20
<center>
&lt;<i>FOA</i> + &lt;<i>DOA</i> + &lt;<i>DOB</i> + &lt;<i>EOB</i> + &lt;<i>=
EOC</i> + &lt;<i>FOC</i> =3D 360 degrees.
</center>
By <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(**)</font></b>,
<center>
2&lt;<i>DOA</i> + 2&lt;<i>DOB</i> + 2&lt;<i>FOC</i> =3D 360 degrees,
</center>
or
<center>
&lt;<i>DOA</i> + &lt;<i>DOB</i> + &lt;<i>FOC</i> =3D 180 degrees. <b><font =
color=3D"#ff0000">(***)</font></b>
</center>

<p>
Obviously, &lt;<i>DOA</i> + &lt;<i>DOB</i> =3D &lt;<i>AOB</i>. <b><font col=
or=3D"#ff0000">(****)</font></b>
</p><center>
</center>
Substituting <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(****)</font></b> into <b><font col=
or=3D"#ff0000">(***)</font></b>, we see that &lt;<i>AOB</i> + &lt;<i>FOC</i=
> =3D 180 degrees. <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(*****)</font></b>
<center>
</center>
From <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(*)</font></b> and <b><font color=3D"#ff000=
0">(*****)</font></b>, &lt;<i>AHB</i> =3D &lt;<i>FOC</i>.
<p>
Now, we can see that triangle <i>COF</i> is similar to triangle <i>BHA</i>.
</p><center>
</center>
By similar triangles,
<center>
<i>AB</i> / <i>AH</i> =3D <i>CF</i> / <i>OF</i> =3D <i>AG</i> / <i>r</i>
</center>
since <i>CF</i> =3D <i>AG</i> and <i>OF</i> =3D <i>r</i>.
<p>
Equivalently,=20
</p><center>
<i>AB</i> / <i>AG</i> =3D <i>AH</i> / <i>r</i> <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(=
V*)</font></b>
</center>

<p>
Similarly, triangle <i>KAH</i> is similar to <i>KDO</i>. This is because &l=
t;<i>KAH</i> and &lt;<i>KDO</i> are both 90 degrees, while &lt;<i>AKH</i> =
=3D &lt;<i>DKO</i>.
</p><center>
</center>
Again by similar triangles,
<center>
<i>AH</i> / <i>AK</i> =3D <i>OD</i> / <i>KD</i> =3D <i>r</i> / <i>KD</i>
</center>
Rearranging yields:
<center>
<i>AH</i> / <i>r</i> =3D <i>AK</i> / <i>KD</i>
</center>
<p>
Combining this with <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(V*)</font></b>, we get:
</p><center>
<i>AB</i> / <i>AG</i> =3D <i>AK</i> / <i>KD</i> <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">=
(V**)</font></b>
</center>
since both sides are equal to <i>AH</i> / <i>r</i>.

<p>
Now, look at triangle <i>BOK</i>. By Proposition 2, we see that triangle <i=
>ODB</i> and triangle <i>KDO</i> are similar.
</p><center>
</center>
By similar triangles, <i>KD / r</i> =3D <i>r / BD</i>
<center>
</center>
That is,=20
<center>
(<i>KD</i>)(<i>BD</i>) =3D <i>r</i><sup>2</sup> <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">=
(V***)</font></b>
</center>

<p>
Now, add 1 to both sides of <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(V**)</font></b>:
</p><center>
[<i>AB</i> / <i>AG</i>] + 1 =3D [<i>AK / KD</i>] + 1
</center>
Equivalently,
<center>
[<i>AB</i> + <i>AG</i>] / <i>AG</i> =3D [<i>AK</i> + <i>KD</i>] / <i>KD</i>
</center>
or
<center>
<i>BG / AG =3D AD / KD</i>
</center>

<p>
Multiplying this equation on the left by <i>BG/BG</i> and the right by <i>B=
D/BD</i> yields:
</p><center>
[(<i>BG</i>)(<i>BG</i>)] / [(<i>AG</i>)(<i>BG</i>)] =3D [(<i>AD</i>)(<i>BD<=
/i>)] / [(<i>KD</i>)(<i>BD</i>)]
</center>
Substituting <b><font color=3D"#ff0000">(V***)</font></b> into this and sim=
plifying, we get
<center>
[(<i>BG</i>)<sup>2</sup>] / [(<i>AG</i>)(<i>BG</i>)] =3D [(<i>AD</i>)(<i>BD=
</i>)] / [<i>r</i><sup>2</sup>]
</center>
Cross-multiply:
<center>
<i>r</i><sup>2</sup>(<i>BG</i>)<sup>2</sup> =3D (<i>AG</i>)(<i>BG</i>)(<i>A=
D</i>)(<i>BD</i>)
</center>
Substituting the segments we derived in part B into the equation above, we =
get:
<center>
<i>r</i><sup>2</sup><i>s</i><sup>2</sup> =3D (<i>s - c</i>)(<i>s</i>)(<i>s =
- a</i>)(<i>s - b</i>) =3D <i>s</i>(<i>s - a</i>)(<i>s - b</i>)(<i>s - c</i=
>)
</center>
Therefore,
<center>
<i>rs</i> =3D sqrt[ <i>s</i>(<i>s - a</i>)(<i>s - b</i>)(<i>s - c</i>) ]
</center>
<p>
From Part A, the area of triangle <i>ABC =3D K =3D rs</i>.
</p><p>
This gives Heron's Formula:
</p><center>
<i>K</i> =3D sqrt[ <i>s</i>(<i>s - a</i>)(<i>s - b</i>)(<i>s - c</i>) ]
</center>


<p>
</p><hr>






